# Spinora deploy & push

When the user asks to **deploy**, **push**, **deploy and push**, or similar:

## GitHub (push)

- **Primary remote:** `origin` → `https://github.com/shivoosingh/Spinora.git`
- **Branch:** `main` (tracks `origin/main`)
- **Secondary remote:** `vercel` → `https://github.com/shivoosingh/spinoras.git` (Vercel-linked repo; only push here if the user explicitly wants both remotes updated)
- Git credentials are configured (Windows Credential Manager). `git push` works without `gh` CLI.
- Follow the user's commit rules: only commit when they ask; never force-push to main.

### Push-only flow

```powershell
git push origin main
```

## Vercel (deploy)

- **Project:** `spinoras` (team `darks-projects-0d253498`)
- **Production URL:** https://spinoracasinos.com
- **CLI account:** logged in via `npx vercel` (user `dark99hacker-9257`)
- **Local link:** `.vercel/project.json` (gitignored)

### Deploy-only flow

```powershell
npm run deploy
```

Uses `vercel --prod --yes` for production. Preview: `npm run deploy:preview`.

## Deploy and push (full release)

When the user wants both:

1. Ensure changes are committed (commit only if they asked).
2. `git push origin main`
3. `npm run deploy`

If Vercel Git auto-deploy is enabled on the connected repo, step 3 may be redundant after push — prefer CLI deploy when the user says "deploy" explicitly.

## Do not

- Push secrets (`.env`, `.env.local`, credentials).
- Force-push `main` unless explicitly requested.
- Deploy without the user asking when they only said "push", and vice versa.
